Pico - The Most Concealable .380 for Personal Defense and Home Protection

At only 18mm wide, the Pico is the thinnest .380 semiauto handgun on the market, making it a best in class for concealed carry and home defense.
Besides being light, small and concealable, it offers easy use, adjustable sights, an ultra-reliable low-recoil mechanism and a tough, durable finish that--with proper care--will give you a virtual lifetime of service.

Comfortable to Conceal and Carry

Weighing only 11.5oz unloaded, this double-action-only (DAO) pistol is comfortable and unobtrusive to carry, no matter your preferred mode. The Pico's flat profile and snag-free lines make it perfect in a pocket holster, while its smooth sides and controls also make it ideal for inside-the-waistband carry--coupled with its extra-durable stainless-steel/polymer construction that is highly sweat-resistant. It will literally disappear even in a small purse, while thanks to its flowing design it will always be easy to draw from concealment when every second counts.

Soft-recoiling and Absolutely Reliable

The Pico is soft-recoiling and makes target recovery lightning-quick after every shot, thanks to its minimal barrel tilt. This feature also makes feeding utterly reliable, even with more open hollowpoint designs or the hotter .380 commercial loads. This means that when you need it for concealed carry or home protection, the Pico will always deliver the performance you expect of a Beretta.

Easy to Disassemble and Customize, Loaded with Features, Made in USA

Like its slightly bigger brother the Nano, the Pico is engineered to be easy and intuitive to take apart and reassemble. Its heart is a serialized modular chassis, meaning that the frame can be easily swapped to accommodate the user's preferences. Shipped with a storage case and two 6+1 stainless steel magazines (one flush, one with grip extension), the Pico features adjustable, quick-change sights with no gunsmithing required. It also offers ambidextrous magazine release, as well as a super-low-profile slide-release lever to keep the slide open when desired. The Pico is made in USA and brings all the reliability and quality of Beretta as the leader of a new generation of concealed-carry firearms.

JUST WANTED TO SEE IF THERE WAS ANY LOCAL INTEREST FOR THESE HIGHLY COLLECTIBLE RIFLES OWNED BY BABE RUTH AND KIKI CUYLER (BOTH HALL OF FAME BASEBALL PLAYERS) THEY WERE APPRAISED IN 1996 AT $60,000 AND I HAVE THE LETTERS FROM CHRISTY'S. I'M SELLING THEM FOR THE OWNER WHO IS A GOOD FRIEND OF KIKI'S GRANDSON. IF NO TAKERS THE OWNER WILL BE PUTTING THEM IN A NATIONAL AUCTION EITHER CHRISTY'S OR ROCK ISLAND AUCTION.

Pair of Vintage Remington Model 12 and 14 in 22 and 35 Remington Calibers. These guns were a birthday gift from Babe Ruth to teammate and fellow Hall of Famer Ki Ki Cuyler. Babe and Ki where avid outdoorsmen who hunted, fished and sang together. The guns were gifted for the purpose of hunting and Ki did just that. Babe had them engraved “TO MY PAL "CUY" A REAL STRAIGHT SHOOTER BABE RUTH”. We have a photo of Ki Ki with a black bear that he just shot with the 35 Rem. As well as a photo of his moose. In the bear photo you can make out the special mount that was used to switch the scope back and forth between the two rifles. We have documentation from Collecting Consultants (Don Flanagan) appraising the rifles in 1996. Don was a sports consultant with Christies for 14 years. postcontent:
Brand new suppressor-ready / tunable .300 Blackout Seekins Precision upper for any AR15 pistol or SBR, with 10" Seekins MCSR V2 Keymod rail and Seekins adjustable gas block. This is a high quality factory upper that was professionally built by Seekins Precision. The 10.5" barrel is Black Nitride / melonite treated which is more accurate and lasts longer than chrome lined. The extremely lightweight 10" MCSR V2 Keymod rail is $200+ and has a 1.8" inside diameter to accommodate suppressors. The Seekins adjustable gas block is over $60 alone and offers you complete tuning capabilities (see below).

This is an awesome package and it is brand new, never fired, $450 cash. Or I might trade for a decent 1911, S&W .357 or larger caliber revolver, NIB Glock if I like the model, CZ or other quality pistol or revolvers, Mossberg SPX, AK, Mini 14, or ?

From the manufacturer:
The Seekins Precision Adjustable Gas Block lets you to fine tune your rifle's gas system for smoother cycling and operation. Regulating the amount of gas used to cycle the action allows tuning the rifle’s operation to a specific load and the use of low mass bolt carriers, buffers and springs to reduce felt recoil. This is critical to allow faster follow up shots, target acquisition and reliability.
The Seekins Precision Adjustable Gas Block is field adjustable. Operation is easy, simply turn the gas regulating screw in to lessen the amount of gas and out to add more gas, then use the brass set screw to lock the setting in place. The overall height of the gas block is 1.37” with left to right dimensions at .94” to fit under most hand guards and still have the customization of an adjustable gas block.
Melonite Coated to reduce wear and corrosion for extended periods of fire, it also makes cleaning easier, as carbon build up will not adhere to the non-reflective coated surface as much as it does on standard Parkerized finishes.

The MCSR V2 rail is comfortable, extremely light weight modular rail system that will work in any situation as well as comfortably fit a suppressor inside the rail. The MCSR V2 was designed to make using a quick mounted suppressor easy to install or remove while inside the rail.
The MCSR V2 rail is designed so that the 3, 6, and 9 o'clock positions will accept all keymod accessories and have two anti-rotation QD positions per side (6total). The internal dimension has increased to 1.8" to accommodate most suppressors on the market.

title: For Sale:  1873 Winchester Saddle Ring Carbine Trapper
postcontent: Winchester 1873 saddle ring carbine was made in 1882 and is accompanied with a letter from Cody Firearms Museum verifying its features, order number, date of manufacture and date of shipment. It's a .44-40 calibre with a most rare 17 inch barrel. It has a three leaf express rear sight that looks like it has been on the gun for some time, however, I do not believe it came from the factory as there is no mention of a special sight. I was looking in the trapdoor and found a damaged rear carbine sight in a piece of cloth that is the early style carbine sight like those of the 66 and early 73 style. The gun has the barrel address between the barrel band and receiver, which is correct according to Madis, and I quote, "Carbines below serial number 112000 which were made with special order fifteen to eighteen inch barrel lengths have the barrel marking the usual distance in front of the frame, from two to three and one half inches, behind the barrel band." This gun also does not have a step on the frame behind where the barrel joins and fore of the chamber, and I quote from Madis' book, "Short rifles and carbines in calibres 44 with shorter than standard twenty inch barrels do not have this step before serial number 100,000. The rare special short carbines with shorter barrels than the standard twenty inch length have forends which are eight inches long in early issues and seven and three quarters in later issues." On the buttstock is seen a stamped banner that has a star inside the banner at the top and below that are initials M. J. P. I am told this is an acronym for Municipale de Juarez Policia. The wear is consistent with a border gun. This gun has seen heavy use and the middle leaf of the express sight has been broken. Of course both sights go with the gun. The guns works as it should with a little play in the dust cover but that could be tightened with a ping or two. All parts less one screw appear to be original to this gun.

The Officer's Model Special was Colt's first upgrade post-war. 

Post-war Colt began assigning letter codes to frame sizes.  The medium frame as used on the Official Police and Officer's Models was the Colt "E" frame.

The Officer's Model Special was made only from 1949 to 1952

It had an extra heavy, untapered "Bull" barrel and the Coltmaster fully adjustable rear sight that was offered only on this revolver.

A new style hammer was introduced, and the post-war type cylinder retention system was used.  Checkering of the hammer, trigger, and cylinder latch was discontinued.  

Calibers .38 Special.
